==> TOPIC: INTERRUPTION OR PERMISSION?

From: Mike Berst <pearlstreet@torchlake.com>

William Ernest Waites' comments about spam raise a couple of good
points, but I have a different take on his conclusions.

Spammers can make money whether or not the spam itself generates any
sales. All they have to do is convince their client that the spam
will work, and sell them a program of broadcasting UCE.

There are probably enough businesses willing to hire a spammer that
the spammer doesn't have to worry about customer satisfaction, he
can just head down the road to the next victim.

Also I think it is a stretch to say that the money that businesses
pay to spammers is part of the Internet economy. In the same way it
could be argued that a bank robber is part of the economy since he
will eventually spend his ill-gotten gains with a legitimate
business.

Regards,

Mike Berst
Apple Journal

Comment? mailto:isales@adventive.com?subject=EYE-JACKING


==> INTERRUPTION OR PERMISSION?

From: Neil Schwartzman <neil@petemoss.com>

William Waites wrote:
>> While I am no fan of SPAM, this observation only looks at one
side of the issue. SPAM messages do connect with some interested
parties. Otherwise, why are all the SPAMMERS doing it? <<

The large spammers are doing it on behalf of small, naive companies
who know no better. Spammers are making a mint promising "confirmed
opt-in" messages be sent, while aggregating their collections from
postings to online forums.

>> Not just because it's free. <<

Indeed, exactly because it is free, or unrealistically low-cost
(robbers have overhead, too -- the get-away car needs gas, for
instance.) Spammers send millions upon millions, with a
click-through rate that would get any honest marketer fired in a New
York minute.

The resource of names is stolen, the resource of the sending
computer is stolen (open relays and proxies in third-world countries
is the predominant manner in which this stuff is sent from the U.S.,
reflected off a computer in Asia, back to North America.

>>It also is untrue that SPAM doesn't pay for the internet. While
the SPAM message may not pay for passage, somewhere there are
servers and designers and writers who are making money from the
advertising messages some call SPAM. They are part of the Internet
just as much as bandwidth is. <<

Then who precisely is paying for the bandwidth they are eating up?
One freemail service noted that 90% of the 1.5 BILLION emails they
deal with DAILY is spam. How does the spammer have any positive
effect on the amount of bandwidth needed to deal with that problem?

Here's another example of a small-time domain owner who has to
contend with a massive influx of spam, robbing him of his bandwidth:
http://striker.ottawa.on.ca/

550,000 attempts to spam, daily. Who is paying for that? The domain
owner, of course!

>> Sorry. I find SPAM irritating too, just as I find some TV
commercials, radio commercials, direct mail packages, newspaper and
magazine ads and outdoor boards offensive if they don't serve my
immediate need when I see them. Everyone of those also places some
burden on society. In the end, however, they do more to add value
than to subtract it. <<

Hey, I like naked teens as much as most people, but I don't consider
spam as being a value-addition to my email box, nor society in
general (with apologies to naked teens everywhere). Commercials on
TV, radio, newspapers, etc. help to pay for the content and
infrastructure which is offered to the consumer, free of charge, or
for a fee lower than the cost of production and distribution, and
room for profit, of course.

Last time I looked, I am paying for my bandwidth, and willingly
(grudgingly) accept advertisements in the content I get for free or
a nominal fee on the Internet. Fair trade, and all.

Spammers circumvent that, make no contribution to content, and rob
us all blind.

Or do you really think that AOL, et al, do NOT pass the costs of the
increased bandwidth and servers they must buy to keep ahead of the
spam influx, on to the end user? Surely not.

Neil Schwartzman, peteMOSS Publications
<http://spamNEWS.com>
<http://peteMOSS.com>
<http://spamFLAMES.com>

Comment? mailto:isales@adventive.com?subject=EYE-JACKING

