==> TOPIC: LIBEL ON THE INTERNET

From: Bob Hoffmann <bhoffmann@wsu.edu>

Mark Neely wrote:
>> (a) It isn't the case that US (or any other publishers) need to
be apprised of "the libel laws in every country". Truth is
universal. Truth, as a rule, is a universal defence in such actions.
The report was erroneous. US publishers, like all others, just need
to worry about being right. <<

While your comment may be consistent in its truth content, it is
narrowly focused on the issue of libel. Let's look at two other
scenarios:

A U.S. Web site says something insulting about a German politician
(or rock star), and

A U.S. Web site claims that the Holocaust is a hoax.

Both of these actions (insult and Holocaust revisionism) are legal
in the U.S., but illegal in Germany. So if I call Helmut Kohl an
@$$#*|* on my private U.S. Web site, should I be charged with a
crime in Germany?

Perhaps CNN, ABC, and CBS should face criminal charges in Iraq for
Web site postings that are obviously crimes in that country! Those
of us who post images of women's faces on Web sites should perhaps
face charges in Saudi Arabia.

My point is that libel is just one issue. This is even more
complicated than the fact that libel is differently defined, and the
burden of proof is different, in various jurisdictions. There are
many, many different kinds of speech acts that are legal in one
location, but prosecutable in another. When we accept the fact that
a Web site posting in one country is subject to libel laws of other
countries, we open the door to saying that other crimes can be
similarly prosecuted -- even if they are not crimes in the country
where they were posted.

Bob Hoffmann, Web Coordinator
Information Department
Cooperative Extension
Washington State University

Comment? mailto:isales@adventive.com?subject=INTERNET_LIBEL


==> TOPIC: TRAFFIC BOOSTERS

From: Jeff Smith <jbsmith@igs.net>

In Ramon's listing, a product called Mailoop was included. I have
had some experience with this product, though I would not call it a
traffic booster so much as it is a traffic manager.

Mailoop is one of a few software products that attempts to put a
simple database and usable front end onto various marketing
functions including: all incoming and outgoing mail, personal
autoresponder for automated follow-up email, scheduled broadcast
messages to all or a sub-section of mail lists, and various other
email list management functions such as subscribe and unsubscribe
automation.

The pitch on profits is more to do with online marketers having
these campaigns such as follow-up email marketing, newsletters,
affiliate programs, etc. Mailoop is just one of a few tools that can
help manage such campaigns.

A final point -- any half-decent software product should offer you a
demo version that lets you test the software before buying. IMC
offers a demo of Mailoop, it's really important that users check
this out first -- it's a pretty heavy system that I found to be a
little difficult transferring information between other systems. So
make sure you like it before you buy it.

Hope this helps...

Jeff Smith
Secret's Out!
How To Earn A Fortune With Your Own Information Products
http://www.infoproductcreator.com

Comment? mailto:isales@adventive.com?subject=TRAFFIC_BOOSTERS


==> TOPIC: TRAFFIC BOOSTERS

From: Cayley Vos <cvos@netpaths.net>

There's a major difference between "traffic boosters" and "marketing
tools". Save your cash and don't buy traffic boosters, automated
search engine submissions, and anything that offers to submit your
site to search engines. There is NO WAY you can improve a search
engine listing without careful efforts by hand.

Marketing tools, such as email programs can be effective for
promoting your business, providing you use them properly and
ethically. In my experience, the only way to use email marketing is
from using a list hand collected by your company. If you try to buy
lists, you will get complaints, as you will be sending unsolicited
information to unsuspecting individuals.

With any product, ask if you can talk directly with past customers.
Personally I believe that anyone with 10 pages of marketing hype is
selling just that: long winded hype. If you cant sell your product
in 1 paragraph, you don¹t have a product.

Finally, I have found that the quality of the seller's website can
be an indication of the quality of their product, but this is
definitely not a rule. I have gotten some of my best information
from the most unprofessional looking websites.

Cayley Vos
Principal
http://netpaths.net
web hosting | search engine marketing | web development

Comment? mailto:isales@adventive.com?subject=TRAFFIC_BOOSTERS


==> TOPIC: TRAFFIC BOOSTERS

From: John Vorwerk <john@4officeautomation.com>

Hello John and Ramon and fellow I-Salers,

First of all, a happy new 2003 to everyone!

Ramon, as you have mentioned Mailloop, this of course caught my eye
as a vendor of a similar (many people say superior) product named
EmailUnlimited.

I also use a rather long copy -- not as long as Corey's, but still a
number of pages. The reason: it works. I have once experimented with
a shorter, more technical copy, however, had to face a mighty
decrease in sales and trial download, and immediately switched back
to long copy again.

So what is the benefit of using a program like Mailloop or
EmailUnlimited?

Next to sending email announcements and newsletter to your list, the
best part probably is the follow-up auto responder. It allows you to
automatically build a relationship to customers.

You can send personalized emails as if you were drafting them
manually. You can send download links in case their first down- load
attempt was interrupted, remind them to read your ebook, offer
support and ask for feedback (I send automatic HTML surveys).

Customers feel comfortable (ok, some say I am getting on their
nerves ;) ) and I can focus on creating better products. In fact, my
success as an entrepreneur is based on using autoresponder to
enhance relationships to customers. And claims that this kind of
tool can raise revenues by large percentages may sometimes be
exaggerated, however, a year ago, when I bought a new computer, my
follow-up system only pretended to work, with the same results as
switching to short copy: sales plunged deeply.

So to go directly to your questions:

a) So what's out there? I'd say more than a hundred products, most
of them trash.

b) Follow-up autoresponders to enhance relationships to your
customers.

c) Watch for good support and trial versions. Don't buy a program
you can't test.

d) Gammadyne is reputable, Postmaster is reputable, MailWorkz is
reputable (although it cannot even send autoresponses), I guess
Mailloop is reputable, as Ramon mentions it, and Ralph Wilson's
readers say that I am reputable as well.

All the best,

John Vorwerk, 4OfficeAutomation, Inc.
